{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502995"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1919"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1919"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.3,0.18,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1919"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the surgical ward review with concerns about his wound seven days after a right hemicolectomy for caecal carcinoma. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 132/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with some tenderness and bogginess at the surgical site. The wound appears as seen below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Broad spectrum antibiotic","Perform blood cultures and await sensitivities","Wound dressing and antibiotics","Antiseptic dressing and wound care","Wound drainage and antiseptic dressing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a superficial surgical site infection seven days post-operatively. The absence of systemic symptoms (normal vital signs, patient feeling well) suggests localised infection only. The bogginess indicates a fluid collection that requires drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound drainage and antiseptic dressing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This addresses both the underlying collection and provides appropriate wound care. Regular review is essential to ensure the infection is not progressing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntiseptic dressing and wound care\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient as it does not address the underlying fluid collection that requires drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound dressing and antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as antibiotics are not routinely indicated for superficial surgical site infections without systemic signs. Unnecessary antibiotic use contributes to antimicrobial resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroad spectrum antibiotic\u003C/strong\u003E therapy would be indicated if there were systemic signs of infection (fever, tachycardia) or the patient was immunocompromised, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures and sensitivities\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate if the patient showed signs of systemic infection with fever \u0026gt;38.0\u00b0C or other signs of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the infection progresses with spreading erythema or development of systemic symptoms, management would need to be escalated to include systemic antibiotics. Regular wound assessment is essential to monitor for these changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Management of superficial surgical site infections without systemic signs is wound drainage and antiseptic dressing","Antibiotics are not routinely indicated for superficial surgical site infections unless there are systemic signs or the patient is immunocompromised","Regular wound assessment is essential to monitor for spreading infection requiring escalation of care"],"references":["Evans HL, Hedrick TL. Overview of the evaluation and management of surgical site infection [Internet]. UpToDate. 2022 [cited 2022Nov29]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com.acs.hcn.com.au/contents/overview-of-the-evaluation-and-management-of-surgical-site-infection?search=surgical+site+infection\u0026amp;source=search_result\u0026amp;selectedTitle=1~150\u0026amp;usage_type=default\u0026amp;display_rank=1#H3089644777"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1919"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18782"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18782"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/61373dbd-6cd0-40b7-9aab-a9b1f21ff29f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/61373dbd-6cd0-40b7-9aab-a9b1f21ff29f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-01T22:54:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T22:55:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1919"}},"c